### <span id="viii.iii-p1.1"></span>The Teaching of the Twelve Apostles.

#### <span id="viii.iii-p1.2"></span>The Lord’s Teaching Through the Twelve Apostles to the Nations. <span id="fr_2368"></span>[2369](#fn_2368.md)

------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Footnotes

<span id="fn_2368"></span>[377:2369](0070408.htm#fr_2368.md) <span
id="viii.iii-p1.3"></span>

<span id="viii.iii-p2"></span> <span id="viii.iii-p2.1"></span>The
longer title is supposed to be the original one; the shorter, a popular
abridgment. The latter has no real connection with [Acts ii.
42](../../../bib/kjv/act002.htm#042.md)<span
id="viii.iii-p2.2"></span><span id="viii.iii-p2.3"></span>. Many hold
that the term “nations” (or “Gentiles”) points to a Jewish Christian as
the author (so <span id="viii.iii-p2.4"></span>Bryennios<span
id="viii.iii-p2.5"></span>), though this is denied by others (so <span
id="viii.iii-p2.6"></span>Brown<span id="viii.iii-p2.7"></span>). A
similar diversity of opinion exists as to the class of readers; but, if
the early date is accepted, the more probable theory is, that the first
part at least of the manual was for the instruction of catechumens of
Gentile birth (so <span id="viii.iii-p2.8"></span>Bryennios<span
id="viii.iii-p2.9"></span>, <span id="viii.iii-p2.10"></span>Schaff<span
id="viii.iii-p2.11"></span>). Others extend it to Gentile Christians.  

